replies.bodyText:
In csvjdbc, it parse time string with SimpleDateFormat. In the constructor of SimpleDateFormat, calendar will be initialized by  the initializeCalendar function.
private void initializeCalendar(Locale loc) {
        if (calendar == null) {
            assert loc != null;
            // The format object must be constructed using the symbols for this zone.
            // However, the calendar should use the current default TimeZone.
            // If this is not contained in the locale zone strings, then the zone
            // will be formatted using generic GMT+/-H:MM nomenclature.
            calendar = Calendar.getInstance(TimeZone.getDefault(), loc);
        }
    }

And In parseTime function, it will get milliseconds from parsedDate. In different TimeZone, there will be different milliseconds.
public Time parseTime(String str){              
	java.util.Date parsedDate = simpleTimeFormat.parse(str);
	long millis = parsedDate.getTime();
	sqlResult = new Time(millis);
	return sqlResult;
}
Is there a better way to solve this problem?

